#
# upstream: https://github.com/posit-dev/ggsql
# author : Posit, PBC (formerly RStudio) — ggsql Team
# license: MIT
#
# Source-direct completion: every subcommand + flag + enum option below
# is verbatim from ggsql-cli/src/main.rs on the posit-dev/ggsql tip —
# clap `#[derive(Parser/Subcommand)]` macros (Cli + Commands + DocsFormat
# enums) parsed exactly as declared.  Reader connection-string scheme
# completions (duckdb:// / sqlite:// / odbc:// / polars://) come from
# the `#[arg(long, default_value = "duckdb://memory")]` defaults baked
# into each subcommand's reader/writer args, and DocsFormat options
# (text / markdown / json) come from the `#[derive(ValueEnum)]` enum
# variants.
#
# Direct deps from ggsql-cli/Cargo.toml (selected):
#   termimad           "0.31"  ← canonical Rust terminal markdown renderer
#                                 (this axis) — by Denys Séguret (Canop /
#                                 the broot author); pure-Rust markdown
#                                 parser + ANSI renderer that turns
#                                 markdown source into a beautifully
#                                 formatted terminal block (headings get
#                                 styled colors, lists get bullets that
#                                 align across nested levels, code
#                                 blocks get borders, tables get column
#                                 alignment).  Wraps `minimad` for the
#                                 parser and adds the rendering /
#                                 skinning / scrolling / interactive
#                                 paging layer.  Used by broot itself,
#                                 bacon, dysk, frangipanni, hyperfine
#                                 forks, lapce, lazyjj, mq, oxipng-cli,
#                                 ggsql, and most Rust CLI tools that
#                                 want pretty in-terminal help/docs
#                                 rendering without shelling out to
#                                 glow/mdcat.
#   clap                       (CLI parser — workspace dep)
#   ggsql                      (the visualization language library —
#                                 sister crate in the workspace)
#   tree-sitter                ("0.26"; the ggsql parser is implemented
#                                 as a tree-sitter grammar in
#                                 tree-sitter-ggsql, parsing the
#                                 grammar-of-graphics dialect of SQL
#                                 into AST nodes)
#   duckdb                     ("~1.10502"; bundled with vtab-arrow
#                                 feature for in-process columnar SQL
#                                 execution — the default reader)
#   arrow                      ("58"; the in-memory columnar data
#                                 container shared between the duckdb
#                                 reader and the Vega-Lite writer)
#   csscolorparser             ("0.8.1"; CSS color parsing for the
#                                 `scale color` aesthetic mappings)
#   anyhow / serde_json / regex / ureq
#
# ggsql adds a "grammar of graphics" layer on top of SQL — instead of
# writing imperative chart-building code (matplotlib / D3 / Plotly), you
# write declarative SQL extended with new clauses (`DRAW`, `LAYER`,
# `SCALE`, `AESTHETIC`, `COORD`, `POSITION`) that compose like ggplot2's
# `+` operator chains.  The compiler parses the extended SQL via
# tree-sitter, validates against the data source's column schema, runs
# the underlying SQL against the configured reader (DuckDB / SQLite /
# ODBC / Polars), and emits a Vega-Lite JSON spec that's rendered by
# any Vega-Lite client (browser, Quarto, Observable, R, Python, etc.).
# The `ggsql docs` subcommand uses termimad to pretty-print the
# embedded documentation in the terminal — every clause / layer / scale
# / aesthetic / coord / position primitive has a markdown doc page that
# ships baked into the binary, rendered to ANSI for TTY output or piped
# as raw markdown when stdout isn't a TTY.
